  "prompt": "What is the difference between quality control and quality assurance?",
  "response": "Quality Control (QC) and Quality Assurance (QA) are both critical components of quality management, but they differ in their focus and objectives:\n\n### **Quality Control (QC)**\n- **Definition**: QC is a **process-oriented** approach that focuses on identifying and correcting defects in the finished product or service.\n- **Objective**: To ensure that the product or service meets specified quality standards by detecting and fixing issues.\n- **Focus**: **Reactive** \u2013 it deals with the output after it has been produced.\n- **Activities**:\n  - Inspecting, testing, and measuring products or services.\n  - Identifying defects or non-conformities.\n  - Correcting errors before delivery to the customer.\n- **Example**: Conducting inspections on manufactured goods to ensure they meet the required specifications.\n\n### **Quality Assurance (QA)**\n- **Definition**: QA is a **systematic, process-driven** approach focused on preventing defects by ensuring that the processes used to create the product or service are effective and reliable.\n- **Objective**: To prevent defects by improving processes and ensuring consistency.\n- **Focus**: **Proactive** \u2013 it emphasizes preventing issues before they occur.\n- **Activities**:\n  - Developing and implementing quality management systems.\n  - Establishing standards, procedures, and guidelines.\n  - Conducting audits and process reviews to ensure compliance.\n- **Example**: Implementing a quality management system like ISO 9001 to ensure consistent process performance.\n\n### **Key Difference**\n- **QC** is about **detecting and fixing defects** in the product or service.\n- **QA** is about **preventing defects** by improving the processes used to create the product or service.\n\nIn summary, QC is **product-focused** and **reactive**, while QA is **process-focused** and **proactive**. Both are essential for delivering high-quality products or services.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
